import java.util.*;

public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        HashMap<String, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
        map.put("A", 1);
        map.put("B", 2);

        // Forgetting to check for null
        Integer value = map.get("C");
        int result = value + 10;  // NPE!
        System.out.println(result);
    }
}

phase2.explanation:
map.get("C") returns null because "C" doesn't exist in the map.

When you try to unbox null to int, you get a NullPointerException.

FIX: Use getOrDefault():
Integer value = map.getOrDefault("C", 0);
int result = value + 10;  // Safe!

Or check for null:
Integer value = map.get("C");
if (value != null) {
    int result = value + 10;
}

Always handle null values from maps!

